Human Resources Analytics

About This Kernel

This Kernel was written by Cong Chen in R and used as personal data analytics project.

Business Problem

Bobs multi-million dollar company is about to go bankrupt and he wants to know why his employees are leaving.

Client

Bob the Boss

Objective

The company wants to understand what factors contributed most to employee turnover and to create a model that can predict if a certain employee will leave the company or not. The goal is to create or improve dierent retention strategies on targeted employees. Overall, the implementation of this model will allow management to create better decision-making actions.

OSEMN Pipeline

  1. Obtain the data
  2. Scrubbing/Cleaning the data
  3. Exploring/Virtualizing the data
  4. Modeling the data
  5. Interpreting the data

3b.2 Statistical Test for Correlation

One-Sample T-Test (Measuring Satisfaction Level)

The Satisfaction has the higest correlation with the dependent variable Turnover, thus I will make a one- sample t-test to see whether the average satisfaction level of employees that had a turnover differs from those that had no turnover.

Hypthesis Testing: Is there any significant difference in the means of satisfaction level between employees who had a turnover and the employees who had no turnover?

  • Null Hypothesis: (H0: pTS = pES) The null hyphothesis would be that no difference in satisfaction level between employees who did turnover and those who did not.
  • Alternative Hyphothesis: (HA: pTS != pES) The alterantive hyphothesis would be that there is a difference in satisfaction level between employees who did turnover and those who did not.
stayed_emp <- subset(df, Turnover == 0)
left_emp <- subset(df, Turnover == 1)

stayed_emp_satisfaction <- round(mean(stayed_emp$Satisfaction), 3)
left_emp_satisfaction <- round(mean(left_emp$Satisfaction), 3)
population_satisfaction <- round(mean(df$Satisfaction), 3)

print(paste("The mean satisfaction for the employee with no turnover is:", stayed_emp_satisfaction))
## [1] "The mean satisfaction for the employee with no turnover is: 0.667"
print(paste("The mean satisfaction for the employee that had a turnover is:", left_emp_satisfaction))
## [1] "The mean satisfaction for the employee that had a turnover is: 0.44"
print(paste("The mean satisfaction for the all employee is:", population_satisfaction))
## [1] "The mean satisfaction for the all employee is: 0.613"

Conducting the T-Test

t.test(left_emp$Satisfaction, mu = stayed_emp_satisfaction)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  left_emp$Satisfaction
## t = -51.373, df = 3570, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0.667
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4314385 0.4487576
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  0.440098

T-Test Result

The test result shows that the test statistic t is equal to -51.373.This test statistic tells us how much the sample mean deviates from the null hypothesis. If the t-statistic lies outside the quantiles of the t-distribution corresponding to our confidence level and degrees of freedom, we reject the null hypothesis.

T-Test Quantile

# Degree of freedom
dof <- sum(as.numeric(left_emp$Turnover))

lq <- qt(0.025, dof)  # left quantile
rq <- qt(0.975, dof) # right quantile

print(paste("The t-distribution left quartile range is: ", lq))
## [1] "The t-distribution left quartile range is:  -1.96062852159556"
print(paste("The t-distribution right quartile range is: ", rq))
## [1] "The t-distribution right quartile range is:  1.96062852159556"

One-Sample T-Test Summary

T-Test = -51.37 | P-Value = 2.2e-16 | Reject Null Hypothesis

3c. Distribution Plots (Satisfaction - Evaluation - AverageMonthlyHours)

Summary: * Satisfaction: There is a huge spike for employees in both low and high satisfaction. * Evaluation: There is a bimodal of employee evaluation for low evaluations (less than 0.6) and high evalutions (higher than 0.8). * AverageMonthlyHours: There is a bimodal of employee average monthly hours for low and high hours ( less than 150 hours & higher than 250 hours). * The distribution of Evaluation and AverageMonthlyHours are very similiar. * Employees with higher AverageMonthlyHours have higher evaluation

# Import Packages
library(ggplot2)
library(grid)
library(gridExtra)

# Plot Satisfaction, Evaluation, 
for (i in c("Satisfaction", "Evaluation", "AverageMonthlyHours")) {
  sub_df <- df[, i]
  breaks <- pretty(range(sub_df),
        n = nclass.FD(sub_df),
        min.n = 1)
  bwidth <- breaks[2]-breaks[1]
  assign(paste("p_", i, sep = ""), 
         ggplot(df) + aes_string(i) + 
           geom_histogram(binwidth = bwidth, fill="sky blue", color = "white") + 
           ggtitle(paste(i, "\nDistribution")) + 
           ylab("Count") +
           theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold")))
}
